The project Migrating to the New World has developed two video installations: 1) Migrating to the New World - part 1 (2017) 2) Migrating to the New World – part 2 (2018). Certainly you have seen a car with a sticker on the rear window which states “Fredrik har lånt bilen” (Fredrik has borrowed the car).  The reason for these stickers is not that Fredrik is a lazy driver and does not take care of his own car, but, rather, that this is a security sign. Fredrik, whose home is broken into by thieves, can prove that the car is not his and therefore the thieves will not get convicted because they do not have a stolen car in their possession. As you can see, this is a clever arrangement for both the car owner and the police and judicial offices.     and other words from Algonquian.

Sometimes at the end of this blog’s entry I have provided some interesting information about a topic in the story.  This story and entry is no exception.

In the story I state that in the Algonquian languages the word for “deer” is similar to “doe”.  Well, that is mostly true.  There are about 30 of the Native American Algonquian languages which range in number of speakers from being spoken by only a few hundred people to thousands.

I used “dei” to represent a generic word for “deer” because each language will have a specific word for the species of deer local to its region. Det er i Norge ikke forbudt at ha jobb og studere.

If you want to work in Norway you first need to be registered in a job or training.

Norway has two types of residence permits. You can get a residence permit for permanent residence or you get an ongoing permission. If you get a permanent residence permit you will be allowed to stay and work for as long as you want. The ongoing permission is usually for 8 years. The ongoing residence permit is usually given to people who gets their primary income from pension and other assets.

Do you want to come as a student? If so you will need a separate residence permit. You can only get one if you have been accepted for study at a Norwegian institution. Please note that you don't get right to work with this permit.

If you want to come to Norway to visit, then you don't need a residence permit. Just don't plan to work.

Hun så på mig
2011

Hun så på mig is a soundart installation that gives an illusion of an unknown figure that can be seen and heard in the background. The figure is an installation and at the same time an artwork.

By walking around the place, the figure keeps changing depending on how you walk around looking at it. From the beginning, you don't actually know how you are supposed to get any closer to the artwork – you can barely feel the figure without walking directly into it. In the same way, you are never actually supposed to get closer to the figure. The figure only exists because you hear and see what the figure is doing. You have to imagine your presence and the way you experience it, because it is always gone and can never be found.
